    "summary": "YES: pre-knowledge of questions contaminates experiential reading",
    "content": "**YES** — This is exactly right, and the reasoning is a direct application of the framework's own principles. If the reader knows in advance that they'll be asked about the Essay 3 progression or the meme contrast, they read those passages in \"test-taking mode\" rather than experiential mode — they attend to what they expect to be asked about rather than to what actually happens to them. This is the difference between first-person experience (what the text is designed to produce) and third-person observation (watching yourself have an experience because you know you'll report on it). The former is what we need to test; the latter contaminates it.\n\nDelivering the reporting questions AFTER each piece preserves the phenomenological integrity of the reading experience. The reader should arrive at each essay knowing only \"read this and pay attention,\" not \"read this and check whether X happens.\""
